Summary of main results 

Our analysis will deal mostly with the case when . 
In section  we summarise its useful properties as a classical 
phase space. In section  we recall some well-known facts from 
geometric quantisation. They concern the dimension of the space of holomorphic 
sections of the quantum line bundle on a compact, quantisable Kahler 
manifold. This dimension is rederived in section  using purely 
quantum-mechanical arguments, by constructing the Hilbert-space bundle 
of quantum states over . For brevity, the following summary 
deals only with the case when the Hilbert space is 
(see sections ,  for the general case).
The fibre  over a given coordinate chart 
on  is spanned by the vacuum state , 
plus  states ,
, obtained by the action of creation operators. We identify 
the transition functions of this bundle as jacobian matrices plus a phase factor. 
The jacobian matrices account for the transformation (under coordinate changes on 
) of the states , while the phase factor 
corresponds to . This means that all quantum states (except the vacuum) 
are tangent vectors to . In this way the Hilbert-space bundle over 
 splits as the direct sum of two holomorphic vector bundles: 
the tangent bundle , plus a line bundle  
whose fibrewise generator is the vacuum. 

All complex manifolds admit a Hermitian metric, so having tangent vectors 
as quantum states suggests using the Hermitian connection and the corresponding 
curvature tensor to measure flatness. Now  is nonflat,
so it fits our purposes. The freedom in having different nonflat Hilbert-space bundles 
over  resides 
in the different possible choices for the complex line bundle . Such choices 
are 1-to-1 with the elements of the Picard group .  

Quantum states are unit rays, rather than vectors in Hilbert space. 
Projectivising the Hilbert-space bundle (with fibre )
gives rise to a bundle whose fibre is . We classify these 
bundles in section  in the case when .
That is, we classify -bundles over  as complex 
manifolds.

The previous picture of quantum states (except the vacuum) as tangent vectors
remains substantially correct in the case of an arbitrary, compact, complex manifold 
 whose complex and symplectic structures are compatible;
this is proved in section .
Flatness of the resulting Hilbert-space bundle depends on whether or not the 
holomorphic tangent bundle  is flat. We continue to have the Picard group 
 as the parameter space for different Hilbert-space bundles 
over .

Finally section  discusses our results. 


