to  for some . This property follows from the fact that 
the number of quantum states grows monotonically with the symplectic volume 
of ; the latter is finite when  is compact.
We are thus led to considering principal -bundles 
over  and to their classification. Equivalently, we will consider 
the associated holomorphic vector bundles with fibre .
The corresponding projective bundles are -bundles and principal -bundles. 
Each choice of a different equivalence class of bundles will give rise to a different 
quantisation. How many such equivalence classes are there? This question will be addressed 
in section . For the moment let us observe that there is more than one. 
For example one can consider the class of the trivial bundle 
, or the class of a nontrivial bundle over  
such as the Hopf bundle. For the same reasons we can expect more than one equivalence 
class of projective bundles to exist. That this is actually true will also be proved 
in section .

